The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A toll-free helpline (100) will be inaugurated by chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee in Barrackpore, North 24-Parganas, and inspector-general of police (South Bengal) N.R. Das in Baruipur, South 24-Parganas, on Tuesday. 

 olice said the toll-free line will enable people to register complaints directly and help cops reach the trouble spots swiftly. Earlier, people could access this facility only from Calcutta and Salt Lake. 

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee launched the smart card on Monday. He handed over smart card driving licences and smart card registration certificates. Transport minister Subhas Chakraborty was present. Transport secretary Sumantra Chowdhury said the cards will minimise the chances of duplication and fraud. Drivers will have to cough up Rs 140 for a smart card licence and car-owners Rs 340 for a smart card registration certificate. 

 Cellphones and watches worth Rs 6 lakh were burgled from a shop in Behala on Sunday night. The door of the shop was bolted from inside. According to shop-owner Apurba Das? complaint, the door was opened by a boy whom the burglars sent in through a ventilator. No one has been arrested. 

 Income-tax official Tapan Biswas was knocked down by a motorcycle at the Rashbehari connector-Eastern Metropolitan Bypass crossing on Sunday night. The motorcyclist and the pillion rider, too, were injured. All three were taken to a nearby private hospital, where Biswas was admitted. The other two were discharged after first-aid.

 The unidentified body of a woman, in her late 30s, was found on a platform of Khardah station on Monday morning. Police said the body bore injury marks as well as marks of strangulation. 

 An alleged Bangladeshi drug peddler, Subrata Nandi, was arrested in Bhangore on Monday. Police said Nandi had been running the racket for a long time. A huge quantity of heroin was seized from him.

 Metro services were disrupted on Monday afternoon after smoke billowed from under a coach of a Tollygunge-bound train. The incident took place at Dum Dum around 2.30 pm, just after the train left the station. The rake was immediately brought back and sent to Noapara carshed. It was replaced by another rake, which left Dum Dum at 2.52 pm. Three Down and one Up trains were rescheduled.

 Two persons were arrested on Monday afternoon for allegedly beating up Sujit Rajack, 20, after he refused to pay Puja subscription to a club in Sankrail, Howrah. Rajack was asked to pay Rs 31, but he refused, saying he will pay what he wants. The club members hit Rajack on his left eye. He has been admitted to a neighbourhood nursing home. Police said four more arrests will be carried out.

 Four labourers were critically injured after the newly-built roof of a temple collapsed on JN Mukherjee Road, in Howrah?s Malipanchghara, on Monday evening. They were rescued from under the debris by fire brigade personnel. 

 A road accident claimed one life, while another nearly killed a pedestrian early on Monday. An unidentified man, 40, was cycling down JM Avenue when he was run over by a vehicle in the morning. He was taken to RG Kar Hospital, where he was declared dead. 

